Stage 4: Econometric Analysis

Elliane Hall and Conner Harwood

Motivation

We use an OLS linear regression to attempt to measure the relationships between different water use types and Great Salt Lake water volume. Though we add controls such as population and precipitation into our regression, our results are not to be interpreted causally. They are mere associations, and perhaps a first step towards a more in-depth project to get closer to a causal finding.

Methods

To try to estimate the effect of water usage in the GSL Basin on the difference in GSL volume between time t and time t-1, we define two models. In the first model, we estimate each sectors water use on GSL volume. In the second model, we estimate total water use on GSL volume. We estimate both models using two sets of data: the first dataset includes data from 1996 to 2014, while the second dataset includes data from 1996 to 2022. The purpose of testing our models on the larger set of data is to see how impactful the 2015 law was on reporting; if we see a drastic change in the effect of water using the second dataset, we can confidently assume that a larger number of people likely began reporting after 2015.

In the first model, we look at how water use by each sector effects GSL volume, while controlling for precipitation and population. Each water use by sector is log transformed since they are right-skewed (shown in Appendix Table 1). We lag all independent variables by one year, since we expect a delayed effect of water use, precipitation, and population on lake levels. Further, we run the model using monthly water use and precipitation, and we impute values for monthly population by assuming that yearly population changes happen linearly from month to month. The results for Model 1 are shown below:

In the second model, we look at how total water use, regardless of the sector, effects GSL volume. In this model, we again control for precipitation and population. Total water use is log transformed, and we run the model using monthly water use, precipitation, and population. Further, we lag total water use, precipitation, and population by one year, as in Model 1. The results for Model 2 are shown below:

GSL volume is measured in billions of gallons in both models above. Further, in model 1, water use in each sector is log transformed. Thus, the coefficient estimates on Agricultural, Commercial, etc. indicates the estimated change in GSL volume from time t-1 to time t from a one percent increase in water use by each respective sector in time t-1. For example, for Agricultural water use in Table 1, a one percent increase in water use by the agricultural sector in time t-1 is associated with a 86.595 billion gallon decrease in lake volume from time t-1. In model 2, water use is interpreted in the same way, but for total water use instead of by sector. The interpretation of the estimated coefficient on precipitation and population is similar to water use; however, these coefficients indicate the estimated change in GSL volume from a one-inch increase in precipitation and a one-person increase in population in time t-1.

Results

In model 1 from Table 1, we find that the effect of agricultural water use in time t-1 on GSL volume in time t is significant at the 0.01 level. Further, as described above, a one percent change in agricultural water use is associated with a large negative decrease on GSL volume. We find almost no effect of population in time t-1 on GSL volume in time t. Precipitation in time t-1 has a positive effect on GSL volume; a one inch increase in precipitation in time t-1 is associated with an increase in GSL volume by 165 billion gallons. The coefficients on population and precipitation are both significant at the 0.01 significance level. All other water uses have coefficient estimates that are negative, with varying significance, apart from irrigation. The coefficient on irrigation implies that a one percent change in irrigation water use in time t-1 is associated with an increase in GSL volume of 175.149 gallons. This is significant at the 0.01 significance level and this coefficient estimate may imply that the irrigation sector is using their water inefficiently, and the water is flowing back into the Salt Lake.

In model 1 from Table 2, we find that there is an insignificant effect of monthly total water use in time t-1 on GSL volume in time t. This result contradicts our hypothesis. As in Table 1, we find no effect of population in time t-1 on GSL volume in time t. Further, we find that a one inch increase in precipitation in time t-1 is associated with a 73.407 billion gallon increase in GSL volume in time t. The coefficients on population and precipitation are significant at the 0.05 level and the 0.01 level, respectively.
